  "text": "The Java Cryptography Extension (JCE) provider architecture in OpenJDK is structured as follows:\n\n1. **Provider Framework** (`src/java.base/share/classes/java/security/Provider.java`): Defines the abstract `Provider` class (line 113) which extends Properties and serves as the base class for all security providers. The inner static class `Service` (line 1500) represents a cryptographic service offered by a provider, containing information about the service type, algorithm, and implementation class.\n\n2. **Security Management** (`src/java.base/share/classes/java/security/Security.java`): The `Security` class provides central management of registered providers. Key methods include:\n   - `addProvider(Provider provider)` (line 494): Registers a new provider\n   - `getProvider(String name)` (line 548): Retrieves a specific provider by name\n   - `getProviders()` (line 532): Returns all registered providers\n   These methods manage the provider list through the `Providers` and `ProviderList` classes from the `sun.security.jca` package.\n\n3. **Cipher Factory** (`src/java.base/share/classes/javax/crypto/Cipher.java`): The `Cipher` class provides the `getInstance()` factory method (line 538 with overloaded versions at lines 637 and 707) that resolves cipher implementations from registered providers. The method resolves transformations like \"AES/CBC/PKCS5Padding\" to concrete cipher implementations.\n\n4. **SunJCE Provider** (`src/java.base/share/classes/com/sun/crypto/provider/SunJCE.java`): The primary JCE provider implementation. The `SunJCE` class (line 83) extends `Provider` and implements cryptographic algorithms including RSA, DES, Triple DES, AES, Blowfish, ARCFOUR, RC2, PBE, Diffie-Hellman, HMAC, ChaCha20, DHKEM, and ML-KEM.\n\n5. **Provider Configuration** (`src/java.base/share/conf/security/java.security`): The master security configuration file that statically registers default providers. It declares providers in order of preference using the format `security.provider.tbd=<providerName>` and includes entries for SUN, SunRsaSign, SunEC, SunJSSE, SunJCE, SunJGSS, SunSASL, XMLDSig, SunPCSC, JdkLDAP, JdkSASL, and platform-specific providers (SunMSCAPI on Windows, Apple on macOS), and SunPKCS11. The file also supports provider preference configuration via the `jdk.security.provider.preferred` property.\n\nThe architecture enables a pluggable security provider system where applications request cryptographic operations without specifying implementation details, and the Security framework automatically resolves appropriate implementations from registered providers."
}

